Conversion matrices to handle rotation matrix convversion from theta matrix and vice-versa

In [6]:
def rot_to_theta(R):
    thetas = np.empty(3)
    thetas[0] = R[2, 1]
    thetas[1] = R[0, 2]
    thetas[2] = R[1, 0]
    return thetas
In [7]:
def theta_to_rot(thetas):
    R = np.array([[1,          -thetas[2], thetas[1]],
                  [thetas[2],  1,          -thetas[0]],
                  [-thetas[1], thetas[0],  1]])
    return R

Projection function that takes world coordinates and convert them to image coordinates¶

In [8]:
def projection(three_D_points, thetas, t):
    R = theta_to_rot(thetas)
    three_D_points = np.reshape(three_D_points, (num_points, 3))
    three_D_points = np.transpose(three_D_points)
    translations = np.repeat(t[:, np.newaxis], num_points, axis=1)
    translations = np.squeeze(translations, axis=2)
    transformed_points = R @ three_D_points + translations
    projected_points = np.empty((2, num_points))
    projected_points[0] = np.divide(transformed_points[0], transformed_points[2])
    projected_points[1] = np.divide(transformed_points[1], transformed_points[2])
    projected_points = np.transpose(projected_points)
    return projected_points

Calculation Reprojection Error¶

In [9]:
def reprojection_error(parameters):
    #Separate parameters from unrolled parameter vector
    translations = parameters[:num_frames*3].reshape((num_frames,3))
    thetas = parameters[num_frames*3:num_frames*6].reshape((num_frames,3))    
    inv_depths = parameters[num_frames*6:]
    depths = 1 / inv_depths

    error = 0
    for i in range(num_frames):
        points_x = matches_normalized[:,i,0]
        points_y = matches_normalized[:,i,1]
        points_3d = np.multiply(depths, np.vstack((points_x, points_y, np.ones(points_x.shape))))
        projected_points = projection(points_3d, thetas[i], np.reshape(translations[i],(3,1)))
        error = error + np.sum((projected_points - matches_normalized[:,i,:])**2)
    return error

Bundle Adjustment¶

In [10]:
def bundle_adjustment(num_frames):
    num_points = matches_normalized.shape[0]
    matches = matches_normalized[:,:num_frames,:]
    translations = np.zeros((num_frames,3))
    thetas = np.zeros((num_frames,3))
    inv_depths = np.ones(matches.shape[0])

    initial_guess = np.hstack((translations.ravel(), thetas.ravel(), inv_depths))
    res = least_squares(fun=reprojection_error, x0=initial_guess, max_nfev=100, verbose=1)
    
    optima = res['x']
    translations = optima[:3*num_frames].reshape((num_frames,3))
    thetas = optima[3*num_frames:6*num_frames].reshape((num_frames,3))
    inverse_depths = optima[6*num_frames:]
    return translations, thetas, inverse_depths

Plot Point cloud function¶

In [11]:
def plot_point_cloud(points_3d, num_frames):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

    for i in range(points_3d.shape[0]):
        x, y, z = points_3d[i,0], points_3d[i,1], points_3d[i,2]
        ax.scatter(x, y, z)

    ax.set_xlabel('X')
    ax.set_ylabel('Y')
    ax.set_zlabel('Z')
    ax.set_zlim3d(0.8,1.2)
    plt.title("Point Cloud for M = " + str(num_frames) + " frames")
    plt.show()

Task2 - Dense Depth Reconstruction¶

In [13]:
normal = np.array([0, 0, 1])
normal = np.expand_dims(normal, axis=1)
max_depth = np.max(depths)
min_depth = np.min(depths)
candidate_depths = np.linspace(min_depth, max_depth, 10)
homography_frames = np.empty((3, 10, num_frames, 3, 3))
for num_frames in [5, 15, 25]:
    frame_index = int((num_frames-5)/10)
    for i in range(10):
        for j in range(num_frames):
            R = theta_to_rot(thetas_frames[frame_index, j])
            t = translations_frames[frame_index, j]
            t = np.expand_dims(t, axis=1)
            homography_frames[frame_index, i, j] = K @ (
                R - ((normal @ np.transpose(t))/candidate_depths[i])) @ np.linalg.inv(K)

The calculated homography matrices will be used to cocnduct plane sweep stereo.

For a plane at depth d and with normal vector n, the plane-induced homography mapping the reference frame to the ith frame is given by this homography matrix which is written in form of frame_index to take care of different frames.

def display_img(img, title=""):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (10,7))
    ax.imshow(img)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.axis("off");

Constructing plane sweep stereo tensor¶

Mapping the ith frame to the reference frame through the plane induced homography. The inversion of H is taken care of by c2.warpPerspective. The size of homogrpahy_frame has additional dimension denoting 3 frame sizes (5,15,25)

In [15]:
img_ref = cv2.imread("./sequence/IMG_1096.JPG", 0)
# Indexed by num_frames, candidate depths, total views, image size
plane_sweep_tensor = np.empty((3, 10, 25, img_ref.shape[0], img_ref.shape[1]))
for num_frames in [5, 15, 25]:
    frame_index = int((num_frames-5)/10)
    for depth in range(10):
        for frame in range(num_frames):
            img_init = cv2.imread(f"./sequence/IMG_{1096+frame}.JPG", 0)
            hmg = homography_frames[frame_index, depth, frame]
            plane_sweep_tensor[frame_index, depth, frame] = cv2.warpPerspective(
                img_init, homography_frames[frame_index, depth, frame], (img_init.shape[1], img_init.shape[0]))

Finding the depth map¶

Finding the variance along the frame axis, and then find the depth index which minimizes it. The corresponding index gives us the actual depth value that can then be displayed.

In [16]:
variance_tensor = np.var(plane_sweep_tensor, axis=2)
depth_loc_tensor = np.argmin(variance_tensor, axis=1)
In [17]:
depth_tensor = np.empty_like(depth_loc_tensor, dtype=float)
for num_frames in [5, 15, 25]:
    frame_index = int((num_frames-5)/10)
    for height in range(depth_loc_tensor.shape[1]):
        for width in range(depth_loc_tensor.shape[2]):
            index = depth_loc_tensor[frame_index, height, width]
            depth_tensor[frame_index, height, width] = candidate_depths[index]

One of the reason the depth reconstructions are not perfect can be attributed to bad inital starting conditions. They could have been more accurately initialized by using the Linear methods to find the 3D points along with T and R and hence projection matrix. Nonetheless some kind of idea of the scene was clearly visible in the SFM case (though not much in plane-stereo-sweeping case,

Another reason for not depth reconstructions are not perfect and have some kind of noise in them. This is likely due to noise in the parameters in the bundle adjustment parameters. More spacing between candidate depth values could have helped maybe. There also seem to be some error due to limitation of keeping the size of warped image as it as the input image. There were some problems in doing it in the natural way.
